ren":[{"type":"text","value":"Obviously, the smaller the p-value, the more surprising it is to get data like ours when H~0~ is true, and therefore, the stronger the evidence the data provide against H~0~. Looking at the three p-values of our three examples, we see that the data that we observed in example 2 provide the strongest evidence against the null hypothesis, followed by example 1, while the data in example 3 provides the least evidence against H~0~.","position":{"start":{"line":84,"column":1},"end":{"line":84,"column":1}},"key":"lSjnpXOmGO"}],"key":"Sa6hrgjIBj"},{"type":"heading","depth":3,"position":{"start":{"line":86,"column":1},"end":{"line":86,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Comments:","position":{"start":{"line":86,"column":1},"end":{"line":86,"column":1}},"key":"I2JPIe5JI5"}],"identifier":"comments","label":"Comments:","html_id":"comments","implicit":true,"key":"eX034Pe1gh"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":88,"column":1},"end":{"line":88,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Right now we will not go into specific details about p-value calculations, but just mention that since the p-value is the probability of getting ","position":{"start":{"line":88,"column":1},"end":{"line":88,"column":1}},"key":"Q5BjDM2Gtz"},{"type":"emphasis","position":{"start":{"line":88,"column":1},"end":{"line":88,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"data","position":{"start":{"line":88,"column":1},"end":{"line":88,"column":1}},"key":"DsFHVcRNEs"}],"key":"LqnHYlJxO0"},{"type":"text","value":" like those observed when H~0~ is true, it would make sense that the calculation of the p-value will be based on the data summary, which, as we mentioned, is the test statistic. Indeed, this is the case. In practice, we will mostly use software to provide the p-value for us.","position":{"start":{"line":88,"column":1},"end":{"line":88,"column":1}},"key":"FPsGYe6VTF"}],"key":"VWQyPBPPpC"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":90,"column":1},"end":{"line":90,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"It should be noted that in the past, before statistical software was such an integral part of intro stats courses it was common to use critical values (rather than p-values) in order to assess the evidence provided by the data. While this courses focuses on p-values, we will provide some details about the critical values approach later in this module for those students who are interested in learning more about it.","position":{"start":{"line":90,"column":1},"end":{"line":90,"column":1}},"key":"CRTMZYAbct"}],"key":"CenAGsNwI6"}],"key":"rfPc821Ebj"}],"key":"ITsy9DoU0B"},"references":{"cite":{"order":[],"data":{}}},"footer":{"navigation":{"prev":{"title":"Overview (2 of 4)","url":"/pages/m15-overview-2-of-4","group":"Unit 5: Inference"},"next":{"title":"Overview (4 of 4)","url":"/pages/m15-overview-4-of-4","group":"Unit 5: Inference"}}},"domain":"http://localhost:3002"}